{"componentChunkName":"component---src-templates-doc-template-js","path":"/docs/installing/ubuntu/","webpackCompilationHash":"e17b8576cdc55202783c","result":{"data":{"markdownRemark":{"html":"<h1 id=\"installing-on-ubuntu\"><a href=\"#installing-on-ubuntu\" aria-label=\"installing on ubuntu permalink\" class=\"header-link-icon\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Installing on Ubuntu</h1>\n<p>The easiest way to install and uninstall Appsody on Ubuntu is to use <code>apt</code>.</p>\n<h2 id=\"prerequisites\"><a href=\"#prerequisites\" aria-label=\"prerequisites permalink\" class=\"header-link-icon\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Prerequisites</h2>\n<p>To avoid permissions problems on Linux hosts, your user account must be a member of the <code>docker</code> group, as detailed in the <a href=\"https://docs.docker.com/install/linux/linux-postinstall/\">Docker documentation</a>, which you can configure by running:</p>\n<pre><code>sudo usermod -aG docker &#x3C;username>\n</code></pre>\n<h2 id=\"installing\"><a href=\"#installing\" aria-label=\"installing permalink\" class=\"header-link-icon\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Installing</h2>\n<p>Follow these steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Download the latest Debian install package from the <a href=\"https://github.com/appsody/appsody/releases\">Appsody releases page</a>. The file is named <code>appsody_v.r.m_amd64.deb</code>, where <code>v.r.m</code> indicates the release tag.</li>\n<li>To install the package, run:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>sudo apt install -f &#x3C;path>/appsody_v.r.m_amd64.deb\n</code></pre>\n<p>where <code>&#x3C;path></code> is the fully qualified path to the package.</p>\n<p>You can now follow the <a href=\"/docs/getting-started\">Getting Started</a> instructions to create your first containerized development environment with a running <em>Hello World!</em> application.</p>\n<h1 id=\"upgrading\"><a href=\"#upgrading\" aria-label=\"upgrading permalink\" class=\"header-link-icon\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Upgrading</h1>\n<p>To upgrade Appsody on your system, follow these steps:</p>\n<ol>\n<li>Download the latest Debian install package from the <a href=\"https://github.com/appsody/appsody/releases\">Appsody releases page</a>. The file is named <code>appsody_v.r.m_amd64.deb</code>, where <code>v.r.m</code> is the release tag.</li>\n<li>Open your terminal and change into the directory that contains your downloaded file.</li>\n<li>Run the following command:</li>\n</ol>\n<pre><code>sudo apt upgrade -f ./appsody_v.r.m_amd64.deb -y\n</code></pre>\n<h1 id=\"uninstalling\"><a href=\"#uninstalling\" aria-label=\"uninstalling permalink\" class=\"header-link-icon\"><svg aria-hidden=\"true\" focusable=\"false\" height=\"16\" version=\"1.1\" viewBox=\"0 0 16 16\" width=\"16\"><path fill-rule=\"evenodd\" d=\"M4 9h1v1H4c-1.5 0-3-1.69-3-3.5S2.55 3 4 3h4c1.45 0 3 1.69 3 3.5 0 1.41-.91 2.72-2 3.25V8.59c.58-.45 1-1.27 1-2.09C10 5.22 8.98 4 8 4H4c-.98 0-2 1.22-2 2.5S3 9 4 9zm9-3h-1v1h1c1 0 2 1.22 2 2.5S13.98 12 13 12H9c-.98 0-2-1.22-2-2.5 0-.83.42-1.64 1-2.09V6.25c-1.09.53-2 1.84-2 3.25C6 11.31 7.55 13 9 13h4c1.45 0 3-1.69 3-3.5S14.5 6 13 6z\"></path></svg></a>Uninstalling</h1>\n<p>To uninstall Appsody, run the following command:</p>\n<pre><code>sudo apt remove appsody\n</code></pre>\n<p>You might also want to remove the <code>.appsody</code> directory that gets created under your home directory: <code>rm -rf ~/.appsody</code>.</p>","frontmatter":{"title":"Installing on Ubuntu"}}},"pageContext":{"isCreatedByStatefulCreatePages":false,"pagePath":"/docs/installing/ubuntu/"}}}